description: Yellow-faced Bumblebee (Bombus vosnesenskii), pollinating some California Poppies (Eschscholzia californica) near Upper Penitencis Creek, at Alum Rock County Park in San Jose, CA.  Although the bumblebee appears fuzzy in these pictures due to its erratic movements, it is still clear enough to see the yellow hairs on its crown (vertex), frons, and clypeus, which are diagnostic for Bombus vosnesenskii.   Also visible is its long tongue (glossa), which it has extended in anticipation of the poppies' nectar.

description:
Soldier Beetle (Cantharidae sp.), photographed on some toyon near the Youth Science Institute at Alum Rock County Park.  This little fellow can crawl around surprisingly fast, so I was only able to get a couple of decent shots of it, neither of them close enough to identify it to species.  

This shot provides a profile view of the beetle, showing some of the salient traits of the family Cantharidae:

1) Long, whip-like antennae consisting of 11 segments.  (They are countable in the photo.)
2) Head directed forward and downward.
3) Elytra that are smooth, soft, flexible ("leathery"), and completely covering the abdomen, or nearly so.
4) Abdomen with seven segments visible indicate that this Soldier Beetle might be female. (Most males have eight abdominal segments, but some can have only seven.)

Other traits of the pronotum or tarsi cannot really be seen in this photograph, due to angle at which the beetle is being viewed or its distance from the camera.

References:
1) Evans, Arthur V., and Hogue, James N., Introduction to California Beetles, University of California Press, 2004, pp. 176-179.
2) "Soldier Beetle," wikipedia.  Retrieved from https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soldier_beetle on 6/21/18.
3) "Family Cantharidae - Soldier Beetles," Bug Guide.  Retrieved from https://bugguide.net/node/view/118 on 6/21/18.

description:
Milk Thistle (Silybum marianum), photographed at Alum Rock County Park in San Jose, CA.  Note that there are four pictures in the set of photographs documenting this specimen:  

Shot 1:  Closeup of pollinated flower head, showing it in a somewhat disheveled state as it begins to produce the seeds for the next generation.
Shot 2:  Another closeup of a pollinated flower head, this one emphasizing the massive spikes and related armoring that emanates fro the flower's phyllaries.  These spikes are on the order of two to three inches long and about half inch wide near the base.
Shot 3:  Shows a closep of one of this plant's massive leaves.  The entire leaf can be on the order of a foot long.  Note the heavy white reticulate pattern on the leaves, which is characteristic of this species.
Shot 4:  A wide shot of the entire plant in situ.  The entire plant is nearly six feet tall.
place_guess: Alum Rock County Park, San Jose, CA
